  "prompt": "How do plant cells undergo cell division without centrioles?",
  "response": "Plant cells undergo cell division through a process called mitosis, similar to animal cells, but it occurs without centrioles, which are structures that facilitate the organization of spindle fibers during cell division in animal cells.\n\nHere is how plant cells manage this process:\n\n1. **Pre-Prophase Band Formation**: Before mitosis starts, plant cells develop a structure called the pre-prophase band. This is a ring of microtubules and actin filaments that encircle the cell at the future site of division. The pre-prophase band marks the cell's division plane and helps orient the mitotic spindle.\n\n2. **Spindle Apparatus Formation**: Instead of centrioles, plant cells use microtubule-organizing centers (MTOCs) scattered throughout the cell to nucleate the formation of the spindle fibers. After the nuclear envelope breaks down, these microtubules organize into a spindle apparatus, which will help segregate the chromosomes.\n\n3. **Chromosome Alignment and Separation**: The spindle fibers attach to kinetochores on the chromosomes and align them in the center of the cell during metaphase. Then, during anaphase, the spindle fibers pull the sister chromatids apart toward opposite poles of the cell.\n\n4. **Cell Plate Formation**: Unlike animal cells that undergo cytokinesis by forming a cleavage furrow, plant cells build a new cell wall between the dividing cells. This begins with the formation of the cell plate. During telophase, vesicles derived from the Golgi apparatus travel to the center of the cell, where they fuse to create the cell plate. The cell plate gradually develops into a new separating wall, which eventually fully separates the two daughter cells.\n\nThrough these mechanisms and structures, plant cells successfully undergo mitosis and cytokinesis without the need for centrioles, demonstrating the adaptability of cellular division processes across different types of organisms.",
